<h1>Color</h1>
<p>Color communicates meaning - guiding attention, conveying status, and signaling urgency.</p>

{{ heading('Overview', '2') }}
{{ heading('Color with purpose', '3') }}
<p>Every use of color in Vivid should reinforce meaning, not decoration. Each <a href="#color-roles">color role</a> is tied to a specific semantic intent — red signals danger, green represents success, yellow indicates warnings — allowing users to quickly identify the state or importance of interface elements at a glance.</p>
{{ heading('Color for impact', '3') }}
<p>Vivid uses a mostly neutral foundation to give color maximum impact. When color appears sparingly and intentionally, it naturally draws the eye — directing attention to the information, actions, and cues that matter most.</p>
{{ heading('Color is accessible', '3') }}
<p>Vivid's color system is built around consistent, role-based palettes that guarantee sufficient contrast across all combinations of text, icons, and backgrounds. This ensures every interface element remains legible and understandable for all users.</p>

{{ heading('Modes & scales', '2') }}
<p>Two color modes are available out of the box, light and dark. Every pattern is built to work across both color modes out of the box.</p>
<p>Colors scales provide a range of shades from light to dark, the neutral scale includes white. They are available in both light and dark modes.</p>
<p>The direction of all the core color scales are inverted between modes: the light scale starts at the lightest shade, while the dark scale starts at the darkest. This inversion allows both themes to share the same semantic colour tokens, reducing the need for mode-specific overrides.</p>

{{ heading('Neutral scale', '3') }}
